<seg id="1">Joint report on the parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway Preliminary remark The modern, united Europe could only cope with the high traffic volume between the partner states without trans-European motorways with considerable restrictions and quality losses.</seg>
<seg id="2">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="3">High-quality transport networks are essential for maintaining and raising living standards in Europe.</seg>
<seg id="4">Ensuring fast, safe, reliable and economical passenger and freight transport is an important task of the state.</seg>
<seg id="5">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="6">It requires a high degree of organizational, technical and financial effort.</seg>
<seg id="7">The establishment and development of a sustainable European transport infrastructure often requires difficult compromises with European and national policy objectives, such as preserving the environment.</seg>
<seg id="8">Precisely because of the necessary environmental protection measures, the construction of the transport infrastructure is expensive.</seg>
<seg id="9">When planning and allocating the construction of transport routes, administrations can, through careful action and decision-making, save substantial financial resources and use them for other useful purposes.</seg>
<seg id="10">One of the tasks of state audit authorities is to identify deficiencies that prevent optimum economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness in expenditure on the construction of transport facilities.</seg>
<seg id="11">The audit authorities should not only draw the attention of administrations to the shortcomings identified, but also make suggestions for improvement for the benefit of citizens and for the benefit of Europe.</seg>
<seg id="12">Summary</seg>
<seg id="13">In 2005 and 2006, the two Supreme Audit Authorities of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic, the Federal Audit Court (BRH) and the Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad (NKÚ), carried out parallel audits of the expenses for the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway (motorway D.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two highways are connected by a border bridge jointly financed by both states.</seg>
<seg id="15">The cooperation with the NKÚ enabled the BRH to carry out an in-depth examination of the cost-effectiveness of the use of funds in the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="16">As part of the cooperation with BRH, NKÚ received data from German bridges and tunnels for its own cost comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="17">In 2000, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany signed a contract for the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="18">According to the planning progress, the date of completion was finally set at the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="19">However, during the award procedure, the Road and Motorway Directorate of the Czech Republic (RMD) made mistakes which delayed the procedure and shortened the available construction time.</seg>
<seg id="20">The contract with the contractor was therefore concluded later than planned.</seg>
<seg id="21">The contractor secured the accelerated construction of the bridge by the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="22">However, the RMD had to accept considerable additional costs.</seg>
<seg id="23">As part of the joint audit work, the prices of motorway bridges on D 8 and A 17 were compared. The standard for comparing the price of the bridges was the size of the bridge area.</seg>
<seg id="24">A price analysis using statistical methods identified bridges with high costs per square meter.</seg>
<seg id="25">The analysis showed that the border bridge under the large bridges with lengths of more than 100 m was the most expensive.</seg>
<seg id="26">This was also due to the increase in prices as a result of delays in the award.</seg>
<seg id="27">The comparison of the prices of tunnels showed that the prices of the tunnels under D 8 are significantly higher than the prices of similar tunnels in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="28">In future audits of the profitability of transport infrastructure expenditure, both BRH and NKÚ may rely on a collection of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="29">Both invoices recommend standardizing bridge constructions and executing steel composite and special constructions only where prestressed concrete constructions are inappropriate.</seg>
<seg id="30">The examination process was characterized by teamwork and an open approach.</seg>
<seg id="31">During the parallel examination, the examiners of both sides exchanged their expertise and skills.</seg>
<seg id="32">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="33">This report covers the parallel audits of expenditure on the construction of the motorway from Dresden to Prague (D 8 in the Czech Republic and A 17 in Germany).</seg>
<seg id="34">Auditing priorities were economy, cost-effectiveness and effectiveness of the use of funds.</seg>
<seg id="35">The parallel tests carried out by the Federal Republic of Germany and NKÚ in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="36">in 2005 and 2006.</seg>
<seg id="37">The NKÚ examined the economy, efficiency and effectiveness of expenditure on the border section 0807 of the D 8 motorway in the amount of approximately CZK 20 billion gross (approximately €690 million).</seg>
<seg id="38">Of this amount, €64 million will be allocated from EU Structural Funds (ISPA).</seg>
<seg id="39">Regardless of the parallel tests with the NKÚ, the BRH had already tested the design and construction of the A 17 motorway between 2003 and 2005.</seg>
<seg id="40">The financial volume for the construction of all three sections of the A 17 of approximately €670 million will co-finance €277 million from the European Funds (ERDF).</seg>
<seg id="41">The Prague-Dresden motorway is part of the Pan-European transport corridor IV Dresden - Central and Southeastern Europe - Istanbul.</seg>
<seg id="42">The D 8 runs from Prague via Usti nad Labem to the Czech/German border,</seg>
<seg id="43">the A 17 from the border to Dresden.</seg>
<seg id="44">At the time of testing, the borderline sections of the motorways were under construction.</seg>
<seg id="45">Both sections were opened to traffic on 21 December 2006.</seg>
<seg id="46">While the motorway is thus completed on the German side to Dresden, the D 8 on the Czech side remains incomplete, since the route section 0805 over a length of 16.4 km between Rehlovice and Lovosice is still in the planning phase.</seg>
<seg id="47">Here the crossing of a protected landscape area in the Bohemian Central Mountains is provided.</seg>
<seg id="48">According to Czech forecasts from 2001, the traffic volume in 2008 in the borderline section 0807 of the D 8 motorway will be 22 940 cars per day.</seg>
<seg id="49">German forecasts estimate the traffic volume on the A 17 at the Czech border in 2010 at around 25 000 vehicles per day.</seg>
<seg id="50">In 2000, the Federal Republic of Germany and the Czech Republic concluded an agreement to merge the German motorway A 17 and the Czech motorway D 8 at the common state border by establishing a border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="51">Since both states are involved in the construction of this bridge, this individual construction measure was an important aspect of the parallel audits of both auditors.</seg>
<seg id="52">Cooperation between BRH and NKÚ</seg>
<seg id="53">Starting in mid- 2005, both Audit Offices discussed collaborating on the construction of the Prague-Dresden motorway.</seg>
<seg id="54">Both sides had important reasons for this cooperation:</seg>
<seg id="55">1.</seg>
<seg id="56">Germany partly finances the construction of the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="57">Planning and construction are the responsibility of the Czech Road Administration.</seg>
<seg id="58">There was no possibility for the BRH to examine this construction project itself.</seg>
<seg id="59">2.</seg>
<seg id="60">The NKÚ had no comparative data to assess whether the funds were used economically with regard to the total construction costs of the bridges and tunnels on the D 8.</seg>
<seg id="61">3.</seg>
<seg id="62">The NKÚ also had to check the effectiveness of the expenditure. For this purpose, the essential technical parameters of the bridges and tunnels should be examined, which should ensure the same quality of use on both sides of the border.</seg>
<seg id="63">Following preparatory negotiations, the Presidents of the two Court of Auditors concluded an agreement on the coordination of audits of the Prague-Dresden motorway on 04 January 2006.</seg>
<seg id="64">The auditors of both auditors met in the course of 2006 at approximately six to eight week intervals.</seg>
<seg id="65">They dealt with current problems and tasks. They developed a uniform methodology for checking bridge and tunnel prices, exchanged test results for the construction of the border bridge and produced joint reports.</seg>
<seg id="66">The ongoing exchange of information was essential to the cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="67">While the BRH focused on comparing the technical parameters of bridges and tunnels as well as the procurement procedures, the NKÚ mainly developed the methodology for the analysis of bridge and tunnel prices.</seg>
<seg id="68">In Germany and the Czech Republic, the legal basis for financial control differs, and hence the way in which the two auditors complete their audits.</seg>
<seg id="69">Therefore, each authority produced separate national reports on its audit results.</seg>
<seg id="70">This report takes into account the results of the two parallel tests.</seg>
<seg id="71">The cooperation ends with the signing of a final communiqué in the first half of 2007.</seg>
<seg id="72">Construction of the border bridge</seg>
<seg id="73">In the 2000 Treaty, the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany agreed to complete the border bridge in 2005 if possible.</seg>
<seg id="74">Later it postponed the appointment by mutual agreement until the end of 2006.</seg>
<seg id="75">The RMD acted as the client of the construction measure.</seg>
<seg id="76">Germany finances the bridge construction to 42.13%.</seg>
<seg id="77">Initially, the RMD provided for a prestressed concrete construction for the boundary bridge.</seg>
<seg id="78">However, in 1999 RMD and its German partner agreed on the construction of a steel composite structure.</seg>
<seg id="79">They justified this decision by reducing the number of pairs of pillars from seven to five and the associated environmental benefits for the valley.</seg>
<seg id="80">In addition, a comparative calculation of the RMD had shown the composite steel construction as the more cost-effective solution.</seg>
<seg id="81">However, this was due to a calculation error.</seg>
<seg id="82">The calculation was based on a length of the new steel composite structure of only 397 m,</seg>
<seg id="83">however, it is actually 5% longer.</seg>
<seg id="84">During the procurement procedure, the RMD underwent serious errors:</seg>
<seg id="85">by inadequately preparing the procurement documents and describing both evaluation criteria and sub-criteria.</seg>
<seg id="86">These errors led to subjective and ambiguous assessments by the Valuation Commission and the Director-General of the RMD.</seg>
<seg id="87">A subordinate tenderer challenged the outcome of the award procedure.</seg>
<seg id="88">The subsequent investigation of the Czech antitrust office delayed the signing of the building contract for the border bridge.</seg>
<seg id="89">As a result, the following summer construction season was lost in 2004 and the total construction time available was reduced.</seg>
<seg id="90">The contractor agreed to build the bridge in a shorter time. This led to a significant price increase.</seg>
<seg id="91">Among the measures offered were the double assembly of the superstructures, the change of the pillar shape and the construction of an assembly hall.</seg>
<seg id="92">In addition, the contractor was unable to procure the originally intended steel grade.</seg>
<seg id="93">The new steel grade - whose higher costs of approximately €4 million were borne by the client alone - made it possible to shorten the construction time provided for corrosion protection and thus the overall construction time.</seg>
<seg id="94">Compared to the offer price of approximately €18.3 million net, the acceleration measures and further supplements will significantly increase the overall construction costs of the frontier bridge.</seg>
<seg id="95">The shortened construction time alone led to a price increase of approximately €5.9 million.</seg>
<seg id="96">Excluding price guidance, costs are currently around €25.9 million net (as at October 2006).</seg>
<seg id="97">Comparison of the prices of bridges and tunnels</seg>
<seg id="98">Both auditors examined the bridge prices at D 8 and A 17 in order to identify the bridges which were characterised by particularly high prices and to compare bridge prices on the German and Czech sides.</seg>
<seg id="99">The study was based on mathematical statistical methods.</seg>
<seg id="100">The tunnels on the D 8 were compared with similar tunnels on the German motorways A 71, A 38 and A 4, as there were no comparable tunnels on the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="101">When preparing this part of the audit, a precise definition of the price concept was important.</seg>
<seg id="102">For the comparison of bridge prices, both auditors agreed on detailed specifications, for example: to use the current price paid for the bridge without VAT.</seg>
<seg id="103">(The VAT rates in the Czech Republic and in Germany are different and may vary.), the costs of special start-up measures should not be taken into account, the exchange rate of the European Central Bank dated 30.12.2005 should be used for currency conversion. (29 CZK = 1 €).</seg>
<seg id="104">Bridges of different types (reinforced concrete, prestressed concrete, steel composite and steel) and different sizes are available on both the D 8 and the A 17.</seg>
<seg id="105">In order to ensure the comparability of the tested bridge structures, the bridges were grouped according to their design.</seg>
<seg id="106">The analyses also took into account the bridge size within these groups.</seg>
<seg id="107">Most common on both sides of the border were concrete bridges (20 bridges at D 8 and 36 bridges at A 17).</seg>
<seg id="108">The study focused on this type of bridge, since the size of the sample allowed the use of mathematical statistical methods and improved the reliability of the results.</seg>
<seg id="109">The study showed that the m ² price of the concrete bridges on the D 8/A 17 depends on the bridge size (length, road surface): the larger the bridge, the lower the square meter price.</seg>
<seg id="110">For German bridges, the correlation between price and size is more pronounced than for Czech bridges (see figures below).</seg>
<seg id="111">On the A 17 two bridges could be found, on the D 8 four bridges with significantly increased price.</seg>
<seg id="112">These bridges were determined partly by a method for determining significant deviations within a sample and partly by regression analysis of the correlation between bridge price and size (atypically expensive bridges can be identified using the distance to the regression curve).</seg>
<seg id="113">However, the atypically high price of these bridges should serve only as a clue to which bridges should be concentrated.</seg>
<seg id="114">In order to draw final conclusions, the causes of the respective high price should be determined on a case-by-case basis.</seg>
<seg id="115">This could be due, for example, to uneconomical administrative action, but also to the requirements for the protection of the environment or other legitimate reasons.</seg>
<seg id="116">Taking into account the larger average length of Czech concrete bridges compared to the German ones (see Table 1), the proven negative correlation between the bridge price and the length expected Czech concrete bridges to be cheaper.</seg>
