<p>
<seg id="1">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Preface</seg>
<seg id="3">The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, underlines the power of the Court of Auditors to audit all public finances.</seg>
<seg id="4">The declaration requires the Court of Auditors to have the power to examine the tax collection as much as possible.</seg>
<seg id="5">The Organisation of European Supreme Audit Authorities (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important component of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="6">The thematic focus of VI. EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenue by the Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="7">One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activities of a Court of Auditors is the development of a specific strategy for the audit of public revenue.</seg>
<seg id="8">This is especially true of taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.</seg>
<seg id="9">Given that national economies are increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation can arise in which national auditors can only carry out their audit activities in cooperation with the auditors of other countries.</seg>
<seg id="10">An example may be the examination of internationally organised fraud, which can lead to significant loss of revenue in many countries.</seg>
<seg id="11">In the fight against such crimes, cooperation between the authorities is necessary.</seg>
<seg id="12">Court of Auditors auditing in this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.</seg>
<seg id="13">The idea for an audit of VAT and the MIAS system is presented by VI. EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="14">In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating auditors first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and the procedures of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="15">On the basis of the analysis of the available information, we selected the test items for the examination planning.</seg>
<seg id="16">Achieving effective and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual countries (particularly EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and increase transparency in this area.</seg>
<seg id="17">We are convinced that the results of our audit not only contribute to improving the work of financial management, but can also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.</seg>
<seg id="18">Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany</seg>
<seg id="19">Introduction</seg>
<seg id="20">Reference: CZ) 06/27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215</seg>
<seg id="21">Exam object:</seg>
<seg id="22">(CZ) Management of VAT after the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union</seg>
<seg id="23">(DE) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004</seg>
<seg id="24">the Commission's objective:</seg>
<seg id="25">(CZ) The purpose of the audit in the Czech Republic was to investigate the procedures applied by the financial administration in the field of turnover tax, following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter referred to as the "EC") with the free movement of goods and services and the use of the MIAS1, in particular the control of turnover claims.</seg>
<seg id="26">(DE) The aim of the examination was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control, with a focus on mutual assistance in the field of VAT, in accordance with the aforementioned Regulations.</seg>
<seg id="27">As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations should be made to address them.</seg>
<seg id="28">VAT information exchange system Based on an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006, the audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NKÚ") and the Bundesrech-nungshof ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany.</seg>
<seg id="29">The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained through international assistance between financial administrations and the comparison of VAT management systems in the two states.</seg>
<seg id="30">A joint final report on the results of the audits has been prepared in accordance with European Guideline No 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI auditing standards.</seg>
<seg id="31">The period under review covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.</seg>
<seg id="32">Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit</seg>
<seg id="33">The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="34">In addition to the 'exchange of information' priority under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925/2004, other closely related aspects have also been examined, such as the registration of taxpayers, tax returns and summary reports.</seg>
<seg id="35">The review also covered the legal situation of cross-border passenger transport by coach and the comparison of statistical data.</seg>
<seg id="36">When comparing VAT management systems in the two countries, differences were found in the following areas:</seg>
<seg id="37">1) Registration for VAT purposes.</seg>
<seg id="38">While in Germany the traders are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the essential criterion for registration is the exceeding of the turnover threshold laid down in the VAT law.</seg>
<seg id="39">In the Czech Republic, taxpayers receive only a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.</seg>
<seg id="40">In Germany, the taxpayer receives a tax code for VAT purposes which applies only to domestic transactions.</seg>
<seg id="41">If the German tax payer wants to make intra-Community transactions, he must request the issuance of a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID number.</seg>
