<seg id="754">The order data are also recorded in EU statistics.</seg>
<seg id="755">Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention Documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="756">A carefully and promptly prepared documentation enables the traceability of the award decisions.</seg>
<seg id="757">In particular, it also provides effective legal protection for tenderers for contracts above the EU thresholds.</seg>
<seg id="758">Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the compulsion to substantially justify procurement decisions considerably narrows the scope for manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="759">The notice of a contract awarded under an EU-wide procurement procedure shall be sent to the EU Office for Official Publications within 48 days.</seg>
<seg id="760">The Office shall publish the notices in the Official Journal of the EU and thereby implement the transparency requirement.</seg>
<seg id="761">The contracting entities must also collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report them to the European Commission through the relevant national ministries.</seg>
<seg id="762">On this basis, the EU Commission compiles an annual EU statistic to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.</seg>
<seg id="763">Regulations of German and Czech public procurement law</seg>
<seg id="764">Equal or similar arrangements</seg>
<seg id="765">Both countries have fully transposed the EU legal requirements for documentation and reporting requirements into national law.</seg>
<seg id="766">The documentation and reporting arrangements for EU statistics are largely the same in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="767">Differing regulations</seg>
<seg id="768">In the Czech Republic, the publication obligation for contracts awarded is not limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="769">The notice period is reduced to 15 days.</seg>
<seg id="770">In Germany, in addition to the EU-wide awards, there is an obligation to publish only in the case of restricted invitations to tender and in the case of hands-free awards from value limits of EUR 25,000 or EUR 15,000 without VAT (so-called ex post transparency).</seg>
<seg id="771">Below these thresholds and in the case of public tenders, only the undertakings participating in the competition procedure receive information on the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="772">Key test results</seg>
<seg id="773">BRH</seg>
<seg id="774">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="775">A large number of the tendering procedures audited were not fully documented.</seg>
<seg id="776">The tendering notes did not contain all the necessary information, such as the justification of product specifications or references to national rules.</seg>
<seg id="777">In the case of a procurement procedure, the contracting authority did not justify why it awarded the contract to an undertaking, even though its tender did not contain evidence to be compulsorily submitted.</seg>
<seg id="778">In a few cases, the documents of the contracting entities did not contain all the evidence necessary for the documentation of the procurement procedure.</seg>
<seg id="779">Notices of award of contracts</seg>
<seg id="780">In some EU-wide procurement procedures, contracting entities failed to publicise the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="781">Further procurement procedures lacked evidence that the contracting entities had made public the contracts awarded.</seg>
<seg id="782">Reporting and reporting obligations</seg>
<seg id="783">The statistical statements viewed contained the required minimum data. They had been created and sent on schedule.</seg>
<seg id="784">Ex-postal transparency</seg>
<seg id="785">Audited construction administrations in most cases published the contract data of the completed procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="786">However, a building administration did not publish this data because of a transmission error.</seg>
<seg id="787">The building administration only noticed this mistake after half a year,</seg>
<seg id="788">so that the contract data of the procurement procedures completed until then have not been published.</seg>
<seg id="789">NK Ú</seg>
<seg id="790">Documentation</seg>
<seg id="791">In the case of construction measures for the organisation of a large sporting event, the documentation of procurement procedures showed considerable deficiencies. These were mainly incorrect information, such as incorrect offer prices in the reports of the valuation commissions.</seg>
<seg id="792">In addition, some minutes of the offer openings were not signed.</seg>
<seg id="793">Notices of award of contracts</seg>
<seg id="794">For several road construction projects, notices of contracts awarded have been published only late or not at all.</seg>
<seg id="795">Summary findings</seg>
<seg id="796">The documentation and reporting requirements in both countries are broadly consistent and implement EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="797">This guarantees the transparency of procurement procedures, including the award of contracts.</seg>
<seg id="798">The rules applicable in the Czech Republic for publication go slightly further than the requirements in Germany.</seg>
<seg id="799">The shortcomings identified in the documentation and in the announcements substantially restricted the orruption-preventing effect of these instruments in the respective procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="800">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="801">The construction management should improve the transparency of her assignment procedures and placings of order further and follow completely her obligatory registrations and report duties.</seg>
<seg id="802">Summary evaluation and recommendations</seg>
<seg id="803">The parallel audits of the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two priorities which are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of works by contracting authorities: the application of EU procurement rules and corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="804">The requirements of EU law enable cross-border competition to create a single European market.</seg>
<seg id="805">Anti-corruption measures are not only designed to prevent or at least reduce corruption. They should also avoid economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.</seg>
<seg id="806">The audit findings of the two Court of Auditors on the application of the public procurement rules in both countries, together with the comparison of these rules, provide information on similarities and differences which may be helpful for both countries in the development of their public procurement law and its application.</seg>
<seg id="807">Application of EU procurement rules</seg>
<seg id="808">The EU's requirements for the award of construction services have been transposed into national law by both countries.</seg>
<seg id="809">Thus, in the Czech Republic and Germany, there is an important common basis for the award of works and the consideration of the essential tenders of competition, the equal treatment of the parties and the transparency of procurement procedures.</seg>
<seg id="810">The construction administrations of both countries have, in some cases, substantially underpinned these bids by further administrative regulations.</seg>
<seg id="811">The Czech Republic has to a large extent also transferred the requirements on EU-wide construction services to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.</seg>
<seg id="812">However, the surveys carried out by the Court of Auditors have shown that construction administrations have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.</seg>
<seg id="813">The construction administration in Germany should further improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to eliminate the complaints highlighted when implementing the EU requirements.</seg>
<seg id="814">The tests carried out in the Czech Republic have mainly highlighted risks which affect the profitability of the awards.</seg>
<seg id="815">For example, incomplete specifications of services necessitated additional services, which were often awarded in breach of legislation. In addition, the cost calculations were usually inadequate. Excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential tenderers and restricted competition, particularly in the case of transport buildings.</seg>
<seg id="816">Corruption prevention</seg>
<seg id="817">The investigations did not aim to detect corruption cases,</seg>
<seg id="818">also because the Court of Auditors does not have appropriate instruments for this purpose.</seg>
<seg id="819">However, the Court of Auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the award of works and how these requirements are applied.</seg>
<seg id="820">In preventing corruption, the two countries have set different priorities.</seg>
<seg id="821">In particular, the German regulations provide for largely unlimited competition, as well as transparency and controls as key elements of corruption prevention.</seg>
<seg id="822">The Czech rules aim above all at increased transparency of procedures.</seg>
<seg id="823">BRH</seg>
<seg id="824">In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which the entire federal administration has to apply.</seg>
<seg id="825">These principles are also implemented in the guidelines for the award of construction services and are geared towards their specific requirements.</seg>
<seg id="826">In some cases, the rules set out very precisely how the anti-corruption requirements should be taken into account when the procurement procedures are carried out and when the persons involved are selected.</seg>
<seg id="827">In particular, the BRH considers that the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tender is an appropriate instrument for substantially reducing the risk of corruption in the award of works. Restrictions on competition, on the other hand, increase the risk of manipulative interference.</seg>
<seg id="828">Risk analyses and adequate controls (especially the multi-eye principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures and various organisational measures are also effective precautions to prevent corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="829">The GRC therefore sees no fundamental need for changes to the corresponding requirements of the administrations when awarding construction services.</seg>
<seg id="830">The rules for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.</seg>
<seg id="831">The deficiencies identified in subdivisions have shown inadequacies in the implementation of some specifications.</seg>
<seg id="832">Construction administrations should further train their employees on the requirements for corruption prevention and raise their awareness of this problem.</seg>
<seg id="833">A substantial part of the complaints related to tasks delegated by the construction administrations to freelancers.</seg>
<seg id="834">However, without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.</seg>
<seg id="835">Tampering and corruption-related tasks should therefore only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can guarantee a sufficient level of protection against inadmissible interference.</seg>
<seg id="836">NK Ú</seg>
<seg id="837">The Czech Republic adopted a strategy against corruption at governmental level, in which the area of public procurement is the most important component.</seg>
<seg id="838">The Procurement Act and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.</seg>
<seg id="839">The NKÚ audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.</seg>
<seg id="840">The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions should be effective improvement measures, as contracting entities must justify the cost-effectiveness of the award of contracts, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential evaluation criteria and the nature of the assessments and must properly document and publish all these aspects.</seg>
<seg id="841">Recommendations</seg>
<seg id="842">The NKÚ and the BRH generally evaluate the implementation of the EU guidelines positively.</seg>
<seg id="843">The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that EU competition, equal treatment and transparency bids are an appropriate basis for the award of works within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="844">The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects aimed at facilitating and promoting cross-border competition.</seg>
<seg id="845">In view of the enormous material and ideal potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the allocation of construction services, both auditors believe that construction administrations in their countries should continue and, if necessary, improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.</seg>
<seg id="846">In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously examined for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to initiate appropriate countermeasures.</seg>
<seg id="847">The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the proportion of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased as open procedures provide a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.</seg>
<seg id="848">A greater division of works into lots can also have a favourable effect on supply prices, provided that greater competition is achieved with a higher number of tenderers.</seg>
<seg id="849">Ensuring that procurement procedures are implemented correctly is an essential basis for efficient procurement activities by contracting authorities.</seg>
<seg id="850">In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised construction administrations. In the Czech Republic, however, these tasks - with the exception of transport projects - are performed by the departments themselves or by contractors commissioned by them.</seg>
<seg id="851">The Courts of Auditors of both countries have the concern to continue to develop the relevant findings for them, even after the completion of their joint project, and to ask parliament and government of their country, if necessary.</seg>
<seg id="852">Both Court of Auditors are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and their implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organisation of Supreme Audit Authorities (INTOSAI). The principles and findings set out above are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and to ensure economic procurement of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.</seg>
<seg id="853">Arrangements</seg>
</p>
