<p>
<seg id="1">Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany</seg>
<seg id="2">Audit Report</seg>
<seg id="3">Preface</seg>
<seg id="4">Taxes are the main source of income for public budgets.</seg>
<seg id="5">A focus of the activities of the Court of Auditors should therefore be on auditing this area.</seg>
<seg id="6">This applies in particular to VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="7">This alone creates annual tax losses in the European Union of an estimated 100 billion euro1.</seg>
<seg id="8">Already at VI. EUROSAI's 2005 congress in Bonn highlighted the need for enhanced cooperation.</seg>
<seg id="9">This makes it possible for the Court of Auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimize audit practice.</seg>
<seg id="10">VAT (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.</seg>
<seg id="11">In 2006, the Court of Auditors of both States audited the VAT for the first time in parallel.</seg>
<seg id="12">The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.</seg>
<seg id="13">As VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the Court of Auditors is needed. This will make it possible to fully assess whether the measures taken are capable of effectively tackling VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="14">The two Court of Auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany Report on inspection</seg>
<seg id="15">1. Introduction</seg>
<seg id="16">Test number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892</seg>
<seg id="17">Subject of audit: (CZ) Management of VAT (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKÚ), audit</seg>
<seg id="18">Exam aim:</seg>
<seg id="19">(CZ) The management of VAT and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. In addition, the procedures applied by the financial authorities to intergovernmental assistance should be examined.</seg>
<seg id="20">(D) The audit should evaluate how financial management has implemented the recommendations made by the Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="21">In addition, additional test fields linked to the VAT should be processed.</seg>
<seg id="22">The findings made should be compared in order to determine whether the tax procedures can be optimised.</seg>
<seg id="23">The audit period was from 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from before the audit period until the completion of the audit.</seg>
<seg id="24">2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit</seg>
<seg id="25">The Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on a control audit for the administration of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="26">In the previous parallel investigation, they had uncovered suspected intra-Community transactions:</seg>
<seg id="27">which made a further examination seem appropriate.</seg>
<seg id="28">As a result of the audit findings, the two Court of Auditors made recommendations on the management of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="29">The aim of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the suspected cases identified should be investigated.</seg>
<seg id="30">The audit also dealt with other matters. This included selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables and VAT auditing of large enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="31">The Court of Auditors found that:</seg>
<seg id="32">1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit</seg>
<seg id="33">• Recommendation 1: The rules governing the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU</seg>
<seg id="34">During the first audit, the Court of Auditors compared the registration procedures for the VAT in the two countries and identified differences which caused problems.</seg>
<seg id="35">The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.</seg>
<seg id="36">This has also been taken up at EU level.</seg>
<seg id="37">The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the extension of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of the persons obliged to pay VAT.</seg>
<seg id="38">The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxable persons and their possible cancellation.</seg>
<seg id="39">The Court of Auditors expected Member States to agree on appropriate arrangements to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible, in accordance with their decision in principle.</seg>
<seg id="40">Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN on the final version of the draft.</seg>
<seg id="41">These common rules are no longer included. The two Court of Auditors regret this.</seg>
<seg id="42">They still consider such regulations important in order to prevent VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="43">• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of Summary Notifications As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended that Member States submit Summary Notifications (ZM) monthly in future.</seg>
<seg id="44">The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be revised more rapidly.</seg>
<seg id="45">Council Directive 2008/117/EG amending Directive 2006/112/EG on the common system of value added tax with a view to combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions shortened the time limit for the submission of the ZM to one month.</seg>
<seg id="46">In the CZ, this specification was implemented by an amendment of the VAT Act which entered into force on 1 January 2010.</seg>
<seg id="47">In Germany, implementation did not take effect until 1 July 2010. It has thus not transposed the obligation to hand over the ZM monthly into national law in due time.</seg>
<seg id="48">• Recommendation 3: Data comparison of pre-registration VAT and ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merging of procedures for pre-registration VAT and ZM The German financial administration has taken up the recommendation issued by the Bundesrechnungshof and has set up a working group to work out possible solutions.</seg>
<seg id="49">The work has not yet been completed.</seg>
<seg id="50">The Federal Court of Auditors will monitor further developments.</seg>
<seg id="51">• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components and approaches to a risk management system at EU level In the course of the first audit, the two Court of Auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.</seg>
<seg id="52">Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.</seg>
<seg id="53">If this is not done, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.</seg>
<seg id="54">The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems which have both strengths and weaknesses.</seg>
<seg id="55">The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Bundesrechnungshof concentrated on German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management."</seg>
<seg id="56">2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="57">During the first audit, the Court of Auditors had jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been exported or which had been declared differently by the taxpayers of the two States in the VAT pre-declarations (or VAT declarations) or ZM.</seg>
<seg id="58">The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the audit.</seg>
<seg id="59">The audits carried out by the Tax Offices of both States had not yet been completed when the first parallel audit was completed.</seg>
<seg id="60">The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. Appropriate measures had been taken by the respective financial administrations (including: subsequent VAT determinations or the prevention of VAT refunds).</seg>
<seg id="61">3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions</seg>
<seg id="62">The audit also included highly risky intra-Community transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by the EUROCANET system.</seg>
<seg id="63">EUROCANET is used to identify vulnerable taxpayers.</seg>
<seg id="64">Member States may participate in this system on a voluntary basis.</seg>
<seg id="65">CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data under EUROCANET.</seg>
<seg id="66">From the point of view of an active participating State, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.</seg>
<seg id="67">As a result, no information could be obtained on which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.</seg>
<seg id="68">The NKU found both normal transactions and those suspected of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected transactions.</seg>
<seg id="69">ZF was able to check sales at high risk only to a limited extent. This was especially true for "missing traders," whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxable person.</seg>
<seg id="70">Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports</seg>
<seg id="71">it is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely to monitor the identity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.</seg>
<seg id="72">Germany and a number of other countries have rejected active participation in EUROCANET because they do not have a sufficient legal basis.</seg>
<seg id="73">The Bundesrechnungshof found that the German financial administration uses other instruments to identify taxpayers who are at risk.</seg>
<seg id="74">However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.</seg>
<seg id="75">The EU Council agreed on a draft regulation:</seg>
<seg id="76">created by EUROFISC.</seg>
<seg id="77">The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be incorporated into the planned network for combating VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="78">4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims</seg>
<seg id="79">Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.</seg>
<seg id="80">Requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are therefore processed in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="81">The Federal Court of Auditors and the NKU compared the statistics sent by both Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.</seg>
<seg id="82">These statistics contained inconsistencies.</seg>
<seg id="83">The two Court of Auditors consider a renewed debate on statistics at EU level to be useful in order to avoid any remaining inconsistencies in the future.</seg>
<seg id="84">If this is not done, the statistics cannot be adequately used for comparisons.</seg>
<seg id="85">In addition, the statistics should contain more information on VAT.</seg>
<seg id="86">An analysis of detailed data may make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.</seg>
<seg id="87">Both Court of Auditors consider that Member States with a low recovery rate should endeavour to achieve at least the average recovery rate.</seg>
<seg id="88">The Commission should assist Member States in this, if desired.</seg>
<seg id="89">5. VAT testing at large enterprises</seg>
<seg id="90">The Court of Auditors analysed the legal situation with regard to the VAT audit of large enterprises in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="91">In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from financial administrations that they considered important in this context.</seg>
<seg id="92">It became clear that the situation is different in both countries.</seg>
<seg id="93">The CZ has a system for the selection of risky cases which includes a large amount of relevant data (including: information on VAT audits, balance sheet data, profit and loss accounts).</seg>
<seg id="94">As a result, the VAT control can be effectively controlled and analyzed.</seg>
<seg id="95">A special tax office for large enterprises is to be set up in 2012.</seg>
<seg id="96">There is still no comparable system in Germany. This makes it difficult to control and analyze the VAT control as a whole.</seg>
<seg id="97">The German financial administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the VAT pre-registrations or VAT declarations and the ZM.</seg>
<seg id="98">Various risk management components, which are still to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.</seg>
<seg id="99">3. Examination procedures</seg>
<seg id="100">3.1 Examination procedure in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="101">Division II - Government Revenue and Regional Departments IX Pilsen, X České Budějovice, XIII Brno and XV Ostrava audited between May 2009 and February 2010.</seg>
<seg id="102">Audited bodies were the Czech Ministry of Finance and 25 CET: Finanzamt (FA) Brno II, FA Brno III, FA Brno IV, FA in Břeclav, FA in Domažlice, FA in Hodonín, FA in Hradec Králové, FA in Cheb, FA in Jablonec nad Nisou, FA in Karlovy Vary, FA in Kralupy nad Vltavou, FA in Kraslice, FA Ostrava I, FA Ostrava III, FA in Písek, FA in Pilsen, FA Prague 1, FA Prague 4, FA Prague 8, FA in Rakovník, FA in Sokolov, FA in Tábor, FA in Vysoké Mýto, FA in Zlín and FA in Žamberk.</seg>
<seg id="103">The Senate of the Czech Court of Auditors approved the audit findings on 27 April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="104">3.2 Examination procedure in Germany</seg>
<seg id="105">From February 2009 to February 2010, the test area for traffic taxes and employees of the associated PÄB Berlin, Frankfurt/Main and Munich audited.</seg>
<seg id="106">After selecting the sample cases, they announced the examination in several countries:</seg>
<seg id="107">• Bavaria, • Hamburg, • Hessen, • North Rhine-Westphalia, • Saxony. In addition, they conducted interviews at the Federal Ministry of Finance (Bundesfinanzministerium).</seg>
<seg id="108">Tax files from the following sites were included in the examination: • Erlangen, Central Tax Office Munich, Hof, Schwandorf, Regensburg, Weiden in der Oberpfalz, Grafenau; • Hamburg-Nord, Hamburg-Hansa, Special Finance Office Hamburg for large companies; • Wiesbaden I, Wiesbaden II, Darmost-Essen; •</seg>
<seg id="109">In addition, discussions were held with the universities Mühlacker, Reutlingen, Starnberg, Verden, Erfurt, Leipzig, Halle-Süd and the OFD Frankfurt/Main, Chemnitz and Münster.</seg>
<seg id="110">The Bundesrechnungshof reported the audit results to the Federal Ministry of Finance in April 2010.</seg>
<seg id="111">3.3 Cooperation between the two Court of Auditors</seg>
<seg id="112">In the run-up to the parallel audit, the representatives of both Court of Auditors met in September 2008 to discuss and define the audit topics.</seg>
<seg id="113">In December 2008, the Presidents of both Court of Auditors signed the Parallel Audit Cooperation Agreement.</seg>
<seg id="114">At a meeting in Bonn in June 2009, the examination teams informed themselves about the initial results obtained during the preparation of the examination, discussed possible examination approaches and agreed on the further procedure.</seg>
<seg id="115">A second meeting took place in Prague from 2 to 4 December 2009.</seg>
<seg id="116">The audit teams exchanged the prior knowledge and agreed on the schedule for the preparation of the joint audit report.</seg>
<seg id="117">The two Court of Auditors identified the following topics for their parallel audit: • Evaluation of recommendations made in the previous report; • review of selected cases of intra-Community transactions between taxpayers from the CZ and Germany, which could not be fully clarified during the first parallel audit; • Review of selected intra-Community transactions classified as risky between taxpayers from the CZ and Germany; • Audit the procedures of the two tax administrations concerning intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of VAT claims; • VAT audits on large companies.</seg>
<seg id="118">The report on the results of the parallel audit was prepared during a working meeting in June 2010.</seg>
<seg id="119">4. Audit of VAT management in selected areas</seg>
<seg id="120">4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint audit</seg>
<seg id="121">4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic</seg>
<seg id="122">Recommendation 1</seg>
<seg id="123">Harmonisation of conditions for registration of taxpayers within the EU</seg>
<seg id="124">in response to the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended that the VAT registration requirements be adapted and that new rules be introduced for the deletion of registration in the CZ.</seg>
<seg id="125">These amended rules should more effectively curb the risk of possible tax evasion.</seg>
<seg id="126">In certain cases, it was found that VAT registration of taxable persons was not cancelled if they failed to fulfil their obligations under Czech Law No 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT Law").</seg>
<seg id="127">To date, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted a amendment to require the VAT to be deleted if taxpayers repeatedly fail to file VAT returns.</seg>
<seg id="128">According to the Czech VAT Act, the FA may delete the registration of a taxable person on its own initiative if: (a) the taxable person has not carried out transactions for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for such transactions; b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under the VAT law; c) the taxable person no longer fulfils the conditions for tax liability.</seg>
<seg id="129">The first examination showed that, in view of the existing legal situation, the FA Prague 1 is required to cancel the VAT registration of "foreign taxable persons" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year, if they were not obliged to register and pay VAT in the current calendar year.</seg>
<seg id="130">The Prague 1 FA often did not cancel the VAT registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.</seg>
<seg id="131">The problem was solved by the amendment of the VAT Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2009.</seg>
<seg id="132">Accordingly, the FA has the power to cancel the registration of a foreign taxable person if he has not provided, in the preceding calendar year, goods or services which are not subject to taxation or exempt from tax and are entitled to deduction.</seg>
<seg id="133">Recommendation 2</seg>
