<seg id="602">With regard to the analysis of such information, the benefits and the way in which it is used further, there were different views among the survey bodies.</seg>
<seg id="603">Some Senior Finance Directorates make such information available to the EU, but they are free to use it or not.</seg>
<seg id="604">4.5.4 Comparison and evaluation</seg>
<seg id="605">As a result, it should be noted that large amounts of information are processed automatically in the CZ. For example, data from VAT audits as well as key figures from balance sheets, profit and loss statements are processed in the system.</seg>
<seg id="606">The CZ is able to control the selection of risky cases based on a wide range of information.</seg>
<seg id="607">The same applies to the evaluation and management of VAT tests in general.</seg>
<seg id="608">In the CZ, the establishment of a Special Finance Office for large enterprises is planned for 2012.</seg>
<seg id="609">In Germany, the financial administration does not collect comparably large amounts of data.</seg>
<seg id="610">Accordingly, it is more difficult to carry out these tasks in the same way.</seg>
<seg id="611">The emphasis is on the selection of specific cases.</seg>
<seg id="612">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="613">On the basis of the data in VAT pre-filings or VAT declarations as well as test instructions, qualified auditors select the cases to be examined and ensure the correct taxation.</seg>
<seg id="614">In order to reduce revenue losses at the VAT and at the same time increase the risk of being discovered for unreliable entrepreneurs, appropriate management processes and risk management systems should be introduced.</seg>
<seg id="615">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="616">THISsegmentISintentionallyLEFTblank</seg>
<seg id="617">5. Conclusions</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation between the two Court of Auditors has proved its worth.</seg>
<seg id="619">Thus, necessary insights could be gained on the systems applied in both countries: This concerns in particular: • Intra-Community turnover, • Risk management at the VAT in particular with regard to the selection of risk-related turnover, • Recovery of VAT receivables and • VAT audit of large enterprises.</seg>
<seg id="620">The audit disclosed differences in the strategies for detecting VAT fraud and the systems explained above.</seg>
<seg id="621">These findings can be used to improve existing procedures.</seg>
<seg id="622">They can also be used to stimulate discussion among interested parties as to which audit approaches and strategies can be used to combat fraud. This applies, for example, to the relationship between Member States and the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The experience and insights gained should encourage us to continue to examine the management of the VAT together.</seg>
<seg id="624">6. Kommunique</seg>
<seg id="625">The report was drawn up in Czech, English and German and signed by the presidents of the Czech Court of Auditors and the Federal Court of Auditors.</seg>
<seg id="626">Status of information: June 2010.</seg>
